        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry insight\n\n- Because E° > 0, Cu²⁺ is **more easily reduced than H⁺**, which is why copper does **not** dissolve in dilute HCl (unlike zinc or iron).\n- The positive potential also explains why copper is used as a **cathode material** in electroplating and electrorefining.\n- In the presence of complexing ligands (e.g., ammonia, EDTA), the **effective reduction potential shifts** — and *that* is where SRD-46 becomes relevant, since it stores the stability constants needed to calculate the conditional potential via the Nernst equation.\n\nFor electrode potential data, I recommend:\n- 🔗 [NIST Chemistry WebBook](https://webbook.nist.gov)\n- 🔗 [NIST Standard Reference Database 20 (NIST-JANAF)](https://janaf.nist.gov)\n- 🔗 CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics",
